<p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300" id="introduction">
                        Scaling large language models (LLMs) remains the most significant challenge for enterprise AI integration. While model size often correlates with performance, the diminishing returns and astronomical compute costs require a more nuanced strategy than simply "going bigger." 
                    </p>
<h2 id="methodology">The Layered Efficiency Methodology</h2>
<p>
                        Our approach at Ostrich AI focuses on **Distributed Layer Quantization (DLQ)**. By dynamically reducing the precision of specific weights based on their impact on activation variance, we achieve a 40% reduction in memory footprint without compromising perplexity benchmarks.
                    </p>
<ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 space-y-2 text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
<li>Recursive Weight Distillation (RWD) for zero-shot tasks.</li>
<li>Sparse Attention Mechanics applied to context windows up to 2M tokens.</li>
<li>Latency-optimized inference kernels for A100/H100 architectures.</li>
</ul>
<h2 id="benchmarks">Performance Benchmarks</h2>
<p>
                        In our recent testing cycles, the Ostrich-70B model demonstrated superior throughput compared to standard Llama architectures. Specifically, we observed a **3.4x improvement** in token-per-second output on edge-deployments.
                    </p>
